recordings.rmk: Unmodified recording except for trimming ends. Mature mixed forest (white birch, other deciduous trees, conifers), and this bird was high in the trees (at least 7 meters up). Fog had lifted but very overcast. 12 songs on recording between 4 and 9.5 kHz, each slightly less than 2 sec. long; sound syncopated high-pitched; each song with about 3 long downslurred notes and the final note upslurred with trills inbetween the long notes.  Sounds a little like Brown Creeper and Bay-breasted Warbler, but sonogram inconsistent with the usual songs of each.

recordings.rmk: The song came from the top of a small tree where another observer saw  the bird in question.  This is not a complete song.  This is apparently not uncommon among spring migrating neotropical warblers when songs can be 'plastic'.  First year adults in particular are still learning their species songs.  There is no alternative I have found given the habitat and weakness of the song.  I used two editing programs to closely examine the spectral signature and compared it against the libarary of songs through eBird.

recordings.rmk: Bird recorded in primarily coniferous section of forest with small ephemeral pond. Spontaneously singing at a similar rate to that in the recording for 10+ minutes. I couldn't find it in the trees at the time of the recording (it was on the other side of the wet area). Although I am not 100% certain, I've labelled this as a Blackburnian Warbler. It seems to be a combination of song types I've seen flipping through sonograms on XC. Please add any comments in the discussion (agree or disagree and why).
